<DOC><DOCNO> AP880630-0065 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0557EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs     06-30 0432</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Political Briefs,400</SECOND><HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0501 to correct slug</HEAD><HEAD>Dukakis Picks Up Endorsement from Union of IRS and Customs Workers</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Democratic presidential candidate MichaelDukakis has his first formal union endorsement, from the59,000-member National Treasury Employees Union.   The group, which represents mostly federal Internal RevenueService and Customs Service workers, said the backing was onDukakis' commitment to beef up the Customs Service's druginterdiction programs and revenue agencies such as the IRS as a wayto reduce the federal deficit.   ``The Reagan administration has been long on empty words andfalse perceptions but very, very short on good deeds,'' the union'spresident, Robert Tobias, said Wednesday.   Tobias also praised what he called Dukakis' commitment tocollective bargaining as evidenced by his relations withMassachusetts state employees over the past decade.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Illinois Dems Chief Targets Jackson-backed Platform Plank</HEAD><DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Plans are underway to strip theIllinois Democratic Party's platform of a controversial plankbacked by supporters of Jesse Jackson which advocates anindependent Palestinian homeland.   State party Chairman Vince Demuzio, a senator from Carlinville,said Wednesday that the position taken by delegates at the recentstate convention here was wrong and will be changed.   ``I've polled the state party and they support our traditionalposition on the Middle East,'' Demuzio said. ``The position takenat the convention is not supported by Michael Dukakis and it willnot be in the national platform.''   Demuzio said he found no support for the position when he polledthe 44 members of the Democratic state central committee last week.   Delegates to the Democratic state convention June 18 adopted aplank calling for self-determination for the Palestinian people andestablishment of an independent Palestinian state. The plank alsodefended Israel's right to exist.   It is supported by Jesse Jackson, who had bus loads ofsupporters at the convention.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Poll Shows Dukakis Ahead in Colorado</HEAD><DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Colorado voters, who have a strong record ofvoting Republican in national elections, favor likely Democraticnominee Michael Dukakis over George Bush by nearly a double-digitmargin, a new poll shows.   The telephone poll, conducted by The Denver Post and KCNC-TV,shows Dukakis with the support of 45 percent of the 553 peoplerandomly surveyed across the state. Bush, the all-but-certain GOPchoice, has the backing of 36 percent of the voters, while 19percent remain uncommitted.   Colorado voters have not supported a Democratic candidate in 24years.   The poll was conducted June 5-7 by Talmey Research andamp; Strategy ofBoulder. It has a margin of error of 4 percentage points.</TEXT></DOC>